@RedStarGuyComrade   What that it wasn’t a bomb. It cost 105 million plus marketing and whatever the theaters take. Which is 20-50 percent of the box office. Which means it needed to make around 270. It made 187. Thats is a bomb. 

What that universal translator doesn’t make sense. “Universal Translation. You hear Yautja, others hear their language.” That doesn’t make sense. How can two different beings hear two different languages coming from one source. 

And as far as the two planets looking alike. I disagree. But is he not allowed to have a different or bad take? No if he doesn't agree with me he is wrong.

@1984ishereresist Nah, Jimmy is more of a lost soul than genuine evil. His rational conversation with Kelson shows that underneath the Jimmy persona there is just a human trying to carve his path in life.

Even actual Jimmy Saville isn't evil,    just a human being like anyone else that was capable of doing evil things. This theme is continued with Samson, the alpha brute and the gang of Jimmys. Perpetuators of evil, with humanity still dormant within them. That is why their characters are so terrifying, becuase they are ultimatley just human like everyone else.

Society is quick to label people as evil in order to distance themselves from the reality that this behaviour is but a breath away from any of us.

@esquire9479, well, we’ll see how that turns out. Especially considering how it’s going to be a film adaptation, when the truth is a story like that really works best if it was a miniseries. 
The interesting thing is that the director you mentioned, John Hillcoat does have a little bit of success in doing a miniseries as he has with George and Tammy. 
Granted, he hasn’t had that much success recently with TV, though as his most recent directing project, which was being involved in the direction of four episodes of Taylor Sheridan’s Lionness, in which the series itself didn’t do so well and it’s first season. But I feel like most of that could be blamed on the writing, not his directing itself.

@Paradigmenigma6292 This same thing applies to game developers too. Like Hideo Kojima or Scott Cawthon I guess. 

You can't really trust 1 single guy to be consistently and strongly creative and clever for his entire life. Some artists only hyper-specialize in 1 specific area while middling it out in all other areas (like The Weeknd). Some artists tend to grow and stick to a single reusable formula, or rehash their peak stuff. 

Dan Trachtenberg is a young guy and his movies still feel like they are being made by a desperately-creative young guy who still cares about being a perfectionist.
